Ethylthio groups add mass and also influence packing of the molecule, potentially raising the melting point somewhat. However, the long chain and the presence of thio groups suggest the increase won't be as dramatic as with other functional groups. - Long carbon chain: base value - 20 (reference to alkanes) - Acetoxy groups: +15 each (limited hydrogen bonding, increased rigidity) - Diethylthio groups: +10 each (due to packing and weight) - Esters typically have higher boiling points than simple ethers or alcohols due to molecular weight and possible dipoles, but don't engage in as strong hydrogen bonding as acids or alcohols, so their contribution to melting point is moderate. - Overall, the compound has 5 acetoxy groups and 2 diethylthio groups. - The long alkyl chain (C4H9) attached to the acetate group will further increase the melting point due to increased van der Waals forces; we can estimate this effect to be around +5 °C.
